Each segment on \(\overline{ML}\) is \(\frac{3}{5}\) units in the x-direction. 2. **Coordinates of Points**: - \(P\) and \(Q\) are at \((1, 0)\) and \((2, 0)\) respectively. - \(W\) is at \((c + \frac{3}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\), \(X\) at \((c + \frac{6}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\), \(Y\) at \((c + \frac{9}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\), and \(Z\) at \((c + \frac{12}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\). 3. **Shoelace Formula Application**: - Coordinates of vertices of \(PQWZ\) are \(P(1, 0)\), \(Q(2, 0)\), \(W(c + \frac{3}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\), \(Z(c + \frac{12}{5}, \frac{T}{3})\). - Using the shoelace formula, the area is calculated as follows: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \left| 0 + \left(2 \cdot \frac{T}{3}\right) + \left(\left(c + \frac{3}{5}\right) \cdot \frac{T}{3} - \left(c + \frac{12}{5}\right) \cdot \frac{T}{3}\right) + \left(-\frac{T}{3}\right) \right| \] Simplifying the terms: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \left| 0 + \frac{2T}{3} - \frac{9T}{15} - \frac{T}{3} \right| = \frac{1}{2} \left| \frac{10T}{15} - \frac{9T}{15} - \frac{5T}{15} \right| = \frac{1}{2} \left| -\frac{4T}{15} \right| = \frac{2T}{15} \] Thus, the area of quadrilateral \(PQWZ\) is \(\boxed{\dfrac{2T}{15}}\).
